"Philip S.Y., van Oldenborgh G.J.","Shifts in ENSO coupling processes under global warming",2006,"Geophysical Research Letters","33","11", L11704,"","",,,10.1029/2006GL026196,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33746418902&partnerID=40&md5=dddf10d6cc5bad40c3342417edb6cafa","Royal Netherlands Institute of Meteorology, P.O. Box 201, NL-3730 AE De Bilt, Netherlands","Philip, S.Y., Royal Netherlands Institute of Meteorology, P.O. Box 201, NL-3730 AE De Bilt, Netherlands; van Oldenborgh, G.J., Royal Netherlands Institute of Meteorology, P.O. Box 201, NL-3730 AE De Bilt, Netherlands","Global warming may shift the properties and dynamics of El Niño. We study the shifts in ENSO couplings in IPCC-AR4 coupled general circulation climate models. First, we compare period, pattern, amplitude and mean state of the Pacific Ocean between the current climate and a high CO2 climate. Next, shifts in ENSO couplings between sea surface temperature (SST), thermocline depth and wind stress are discussed. Although the mean state shifts, the overall ENSO properties do not change much. Changes in the mean state affect the feedback loop. Higher mean SST provides higher damping through cloud feedback. The shallower thermocline and mixed layer depth increase SST sensitivity to thermocline variability and wind stress. Wind response to SST variability increases where the mean SST has increased the most. However, the higher damping and more stable atmosphere compensate the other changes and the residual change in ENSO properties is relatively small. Copyright 2006 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Ocean currents; Temperature distribution; Wind; Coupled general circulation climate models; El Nino-Southern Oscillation (ENSO); Feedback loop; Sea surface temperature (SST); Global warming; atmosphere-ocean coupling; El Nino-Southern Oscillation; general circulation model; global warming; sea surface temperature; thermocline; wind stress",,,,,,"Boulanger, J.-P., Durand, E., Duvel, J.-P., Menkes, C., Delecluse, P., Imbard, M., Lengaigne, M., Masson, S., Role of non-linear ocean processes to westerly wind events: New implications for the 1997 El Niño onset (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett., 28, pp. 1603-1606; Burgers, G.J.H., van Oldenborgh, G.J., On the impact of local feedbacks in the central Pacific on the ENSO cycle (2002) J. Clim., 16, pp. 2396-2407; Capotondi, A., Wittenberg, A., Masina, S., Spatial and temporal structure of ENSO in 20th century coupled simulations (2006) Ocean Modell., , in press; Guilyardi, E., El Niño-mean state-seasonal cycle interactions in a multi-model ensemble (2006) Clim. Dyn., 26, pp. 329-348; Kirtman, B., Oceanic Rossby wave dynamics and the ENSO period in a coupled model (1997) J. Clim., 10, pp. 1690-1704; Liu, Z., Vavrus, S., He, F., Wen, N., Zhong, Y., Rethinking tropical ocean response to global warming: The enhanced equatorial warming (2005) J. Clim., 18, pp. 4684-4700; McPhaden, M.J., The Tropical Ocean Global Atmosphere (TOGA) observing system: A decade of progress (1998) J. Geophys. Res., 103, pp. 14,169-14,240; Merryfield, W.J., Changes in ENSO under CO2 doubling in the IPCC AR4 coupled climate models (2006) J. Clim., , in press; Toniazzo, T., Properties of the El Niño Southern Oscillation in different equilibrium climates with the HadCM3 model (2006) J. Clim., , in press; Van Oldenborgh, G.J., Philip, S.Y., Collins, M., El Niño in a changing climate: A multi-model study (2005) Ocean Sci., 1, pp. 81-95; Von Storch, H., Zwiers, F., (2001) Statistical Analysis in Climate Research, p. 84. , Cambridge Univ. Press, New York; Zelle, H., Appeldoorn, G., Burgers, G., van Oldenborgh, G.J., On the relationship between sea surface temperature and thermocline depth in the eastern equatorial Pacific (2004) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 34, pp. 643-655; Zelle, H., Van Oldenborgh, G.J., Burgers, G., Dijkstra, H.A., El Niño and greenhouse warming: Results from ensemble simulations with the NCAR CCSM (2005) J. Cl